@{B}Driving@{UB}


When you enter the cab from the @{" Options Screen " LINK "Options_Screen"} you
will see the drivers view through the cab window on the left,
and the data display on the right. Below these are the dashboard indicators,
and between them are the driver's indicator @{" Lights " LINK "Lights"}
and the milepost symbol.

You may also notice a small horizontal red line which indicates when
the horizon is level. Watching the horizon (not the red line!) gives warning of changing gradients.

For a view of these features see the @{"Help pic" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/multiview TD3A:Help SCREEN"}

If you start at a stand the @{" AWS " LINK "AWS"} @{" horn " LINK TD3a:fx/aws.snd/main}
will be sounding and will need
to be cancelled with "a". Press "f" to put the motors into Forward and when the
"R" appears below the signal number, (after a few seconds and only in a station),
you may depart.(If you get bored of waiting, press "6" to speed up time.)
The bottom row of @{" keys " LINK "keys"} control the brakes and power.
So press "z" to release the brakes and then "." or ">" to notch up the power.
Watch the gradient and speed to make sure you don't roll back.

@{b}Steam locos@{ub} require much more work!


@{B}Starting@{UB}


To start off, first ensure that the cylinder cocks are open (e) and C is displayed.
Then press F to select the direction you will be turning the cut-off reversing wheel
Cut-off (k) will need to be maximum to start and then reduced (shift K) as speed increases.
Open the regulator (>) to supply steam to the cylinders and the cut-off to increase the
amount of time the steam is kept in the cylinder, and hence the force applied and steam used.
Release the vacuum brakes (z), and you will start to move. You may then switch off the blower (y)
Give a toot on the whistle (h) and apply sand (u) if required.


@{B}Cylinder Cock@{UB}


Key e

C displayed when open


The cylinder cock must be open when the loco is first started (when F is pressed)
to allow steam which condenses into water to escape when the cylinder is cold
The cylinder cock should then remain shut.


@{b}Steam pressure@{ub}


First ensure you have more than 200 on the steam pressure gauge or you will have insufficient
pressure to releasec the brakes. To raise pressure you will need to get a hot fire and sufficient water in
the boiler using the injectors. Also the more steam you use the pressure will fall.
The cut-off valves, blower, whistle and regulator all use valuable steam reducing the
pressure so use them all sparingly.


Pressure:

Below 200  No Power and brakes will be applied as vacuum is lost
200 - 250  Reduced Power
250 - 300  Full working pressure
Above 300  Safety valves will operate wasting steam


@{b}Water@{ub}


Introduce water into the boiler from the water tank using injectors

i        increase injector pressure
shift I  reduce injector pressure.

For greatest efficiency keep the water level near the centre mark.
Too much water may force water into the cylinders, too little may melt
the fusible lead plugs in the base of the boiler extinguishing the fire,
or even cause a boiler explosion!
Remember gradients will also effect the water level gauge.


@{b}Fire@{ub}


Open the fire doors (left arrow key) and fill the fire with coal (up arrow key)
until the fire grows dimmer.
If the fire turns black you have smothered it and you will have to wait for the temperature to
rise again (see thermometer gauge). For optimum efficiency keep the fire near the centre marking
and glowing red.

@{b}Air@{ub}


Air is fed to the firebox through dampers and through the doors.

d        increase damping
shift D  reduce damping

More damping is required to get cold or over-filled fires going
Normally use level 4/5 for dampers and have the fire door almost closed for optimum performance
once the fire is going.


@{b}Cut-Off Valves@{ub}


These keep the steam in the cylinders for a variable time.
Full cut-off is required when starting, and it should then be reduced
as speed increases to save steam.

k        increase cut-off
shift K  reduce  cut-off

Optimum speeds for cut-off levels

0 - 12  Full (5)  75%
12- 28  4         60%
28- 44  3         45%
44- 56  2         30%
56- 72  1         15%
72+     0        <15%

Cut-off should also be at 0 when selecting direction with keys O,F and R



@{b}Blower@{ub}


Key y

B displayed when on


The blower is used to force steam through the chimney when the regulator is
off, or when the train is in a tunnel. Failure to have the blower on could result
in blow-back which could blow the contents of the fire-box into the cab!
However the blower should be switched off when not required to save steam.


@{b}Regulator@{ub}


This controls the amount of steam delivered to the cylinders and works
similarly to the normal power controller and uses the same keys.
Remember you will have no power unless you have sufficient steam pressure.


