@NODE "Signals" "Signals"
@TOC "MAIN"


@{"Signals picture " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/multiview TD3A:Signals.iff SCREEN"}


There are many types of signal as shown on the picture linked above.
The normal sequences are also indicated.

@{B}Colour lights@{UB} may have two, three or four aspects.
Colour lights normal sequence is double yellow (where available), single yellow and then the red signal.

@{B}Semaphore signals@{UB} are spaced according to signalbox locations.
On the approach to the signalbox is the home stop signal which is red and horizontal (or red light at night)
or raised at 45 degrees (green) if the line is clear.
The next signal is also a usually a stop signal protecting the section to the next signal box ahead.
Generally about half a mile or more from each box you will see the distant signal
This is yellow and indicates the position of the following stop signals. If it is raised (green)
all the stop signals for the following box are clear. If horizontal (yellow) then be prepared to stop at
the next stop signal.
There are variations such as section and distant signals for the next box on the same post
and fixed distant signals which are always horizontal usually approaching a line speed reduction or other hazards,
or the end of the line.

The distance from the next signal is shown on the display in yards.

If any signal shows red, you must stop within 35 yards of it to get the
message from the signalman.

He may ask you to pass the signal at danger.
If so you should give a long blast on the horn and proceed cautiously
until passing the next signal. Remember the next signal may be red.

Your speed passing a signal with two yellows (where available) should generally be below 90mph
and at one yellow try to reduce your speed to 60mph.
If you can see a red signal and you're over 60mph you will struggle to stop.
However, beware of signals closer together than usual, and reduce your speed
accordingly.

A hint to assist stopping is to keep your speed well below
one tenth of the number of yards from the stopping point.

Flashing yellows countdown to a high speed junction, generally 30 to 70mph.

A junction signal either has a letter above, eg S for Slow Line or
F for Fast Line, or has five white lights diagonally displayed,
indicating the direction of the crossover.

Other signals may have a number displayed indicating the platform that
you will enter, or the line you are crossing to.

Junctions without flashing yellow signals are protected by red signals which
will change as the train passes over the @{" AWS " LINK "AWS"} magnet if the
route is set and the line is clear.

These junction speeds vary between 10 and 40 mph.

A warning board will be shown approaching the junction signal
indicating the junction speed, and the speed limit board will
also be seen indicating the position of the junction.

If you are detained at a red signal for a couple of minutes the guard will
announce the reason for the delay to the passengers and it will be displayed on the
Message Display and in the log.



@{b}RETB Remote Electric Token Block@{ub}


This system is used on long rural routes mainly in Scotland and Wales, and
enables one signalman to control many miles of track from a remote location.

Generally the sequence of signals is as follows

Fixed Distant

A horizontal fixed yellow semaphore arm, usually on a reflectorised board.
This warns the driver that one of the other signals below is approaching
and that he may need to stop shortly

Points Set indicator

This signals shows a yellow light when the points are safely set for the train to proceed
Note that this signal will be unlit and difficult to see at night if the points are not set,
and the train must be stopped if this is the case.

Stop for Token board

This is a reflectorised large white board with a red circle displayed
The train must always be brought to a stand at this board and the driver must wait
for the Token Issued message from the signalman before proceeding

